// BindingService — org-scoped pod-to-pod binding lifecycle.
//
// Migrated from REST handlers in backend/internal/api/rest/v1/bindings*.go
// per .claude/plans/proto-naming-conventions.md. Conventions enforced:
//   * package proto.binding.v1 + go_package suffix for dispatch
//   * service name = <Domain>Service, methods PascalCase verbs
//   * snake_case fields, no json_name annotations
//   * org_slug at field 1 of every request (no path params on Connect URLs)
//   * initiator_pod replaces the REST X-Pod-Key header (binary wire has no
//     extra-protocol headers — the calling pod is part of the message body)
//   * timestamps as string ISO-8601 (no google.protobuf.Timestamp)
//   * list response = {items, total, limit, offset} uniform envelope
//
// Field set reconciled across three layers (runbook §1.5):
//   - backend domain/channel/binding_model.go        (12 fields on PodBinding)
//   - clients/core/crates/types/src/binding.rs       (8 fields — drifted set,
//     uses source_pod/target_pod naming, missing granted_scopes/pending_scopes
//     split; fixed in this PR)
//   - clients/web/src/lib/api/* (no UI call sites today — runner reaches the
//     domain through MCP-over-gRPC; the REST surface exists for the Desktop
//     node-bridge + Web wasm bridge that nothing currently invokes)
//
// Auth model (DEVIATION from runbook §3.5):
//   The REST handler authenticates via the X-Pod-Key header instead of
//   Bearer JWT — binding endpoints are pod-scoped, not user-scoped.
//   Connect-RPC moves auth back to the standard Bearer + ResolveOrgScope
//   path (the user is authenticated and scoped to an org; the calling pod
//   is named explicitly in `initiator_pod`). Pod-membership enforcement
//   stays at the service layer (the existing binding.Service mutates pods
//   the caller passes in — it never re-validates pod ownership against
//   user identity), so this is a parity-preserving move.

